  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** falls under **criminal legislation** in most jurisdictions worldwide. It is considered a serious financial crime because it involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems.\n\n### Key points:\n1. **Definition**: Money laundering is the process of making illegally gained proceeds (from activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, etc.) appear legal by disguising their true source.\n   \n2. **Criminalization**: It is explicitly criminalized in many countries under specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws. For example:\n   - In the **United States**, it is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)**.\n   - In the **European Union**, it is governed by the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**.\n   - In **India**, the **Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA), 2002** addresses this crime.\n\n3. **Penalties**: Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, forfeiture of assets, and imprisonment. In some jurisdictions, individuals or entities involved may also face civil penalties or restrictions on their business operations.\n\n4. **Global Coordination**: International bodies like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** provide guidelines and standards to combat money laundering, and countries often cooperate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering activities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a criminal offense subject to strict legal consequences under criminal legislation in most legal systems.",
